<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-157-277 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 832 846</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  May 9 1991 v39 n9 p135(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fast bus networks CPUs, DSPs, to build multimedia systems.andO;(central processing units, digital signal processors) (ProductInnovation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bursky, Dave.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Spectrum Signal Processing's Media-Link Controller is intended toovercome bottlenecks in digital signal processing (DSP) systems byforming a high-speed interconnection system allowing DSP chips, ahost processor and I/O peripherals to communicate together over ahigh-speed bus, independent of the host-system bus.andP;  Multipleprocessors can thus be interconnected to form systems to whichprocessing power or I/O functions can be added, much as memory isadded to a computer.andP;  The Media-Link Controller transfers16-bit-wide data at sustained rates of 66Mbytes per second; itmatches the control signals of a host Intel 80386 32-bit processoror Texas Instruments 32-bit TMS320C31 floating-point DSP chip inaddition to controlling the interconnection scheme.andP;  On-chip logicsupports direct connection to the desired processor and keeps theinterface simple.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Spectrum Signal Processing Inc. (Innovations).andO;Product:   Spectrum Signal Processing Media-Link (Integrated circuit) (Designand construction).andO;Topic:     Digital Signal ProcessingCircuit DesignConnectivityI/O Boards/CardsTransmission SpeedNew TechniqueIntegrated circuits.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Spectrum Signal Processing's Media-Link Controller design. (chart)An 80386-based PC/AT card uses to Media-Link Controller chips.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>